macroeconomic theory and political economy siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project macroeconomic theory and political economy title macroeconomic theory and political economy principal investigator manuel amador dates september 15 2011 september 15 2013 the project lies at the intersection of macroeconomic theory and political economy it deals with three sets of questions which are linked by a common methodological approach they use the tools of dynamic modern macro theory to answer questions that are relevant for policy the first set of questions centers on the interaction of sovereign debt and political economy in emerging markets and the implications of this interaction for debt repayment economic growth and the volatility of the business cycle the second related part of my research agenda focuses on optimal policy design when politicians are subject to biases in their decisions but posses private information that is valuable for taking efficient decisions the third part of my research agenda studies policy design when policy makers and agents have incomplete information and learn through market interactions and public announcements stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
